      },
      "conclusion": "L2 hit rates are stable ~78-80% for most sizes. 2K anomaly at 63.1% may be tile/cache alignment issue. GEMM L2 behavior is consistent across sizes."
    },
    {
      "experiment_id": "exp_002_l2_rccl_overlap",
      "timestamp": "2026-03-19T15:26:51.726361",
      "hypothesis": "L2 hit rate drops significantly when GEMM runs alongside RCCL due to cache evictions",
      "configuration": {
        "backend": "ws",
        "gpus": 8,
        "counters": "TCC_HIT_sum, TCC_MISS_sum",
        "sizes": [
          1024,
          2048,
          4096,
          8192
        ],
        "collective": "all_reduce"
      },
      "results": {
        "l2_hit_rate_alone": {
          "1024": 79.3,
          "2048": 63.1,
          "4096": 80.2,
          "8192": 78.1
        },
        "l2_hit_rate_rccl": {
          "1024": 79.4,
          "2048": 62.9,
          "4096": 80.3,
          "8192": 78.3
        },
        "l2_delta": {
          "1024": "+0.1%",
          "2048": "-0.2%",
          "4096": "+0.1%",
          "8192": "+0.2%"
        },
        "nccl_l2_hit_rate": 49.5
      },
      "conclusion": "HYPOTHESIS REFUTED. GEMM L2 hit rates are COMPLETELY UNAFFECTED by RCCL overlap (delta < 0.3%). This confirms that MI300X's per-XCD, non-coherent L2 provides isolation between concurrent kernels. NCCL kernels themselves have ~50% L2 hit rate (essentially random). The GEMM performance degradation during overlap is NOT caused by L2 thrashing.",
      "implications": [
        "L2 (TCC) is NOT the bottleneck in compute-communication overlap on MI300X",
        "MALL/LLC (coherent, cross-XCD) analysis is critical \u2014 needs df-counters",
        "HBM bandwidth contention is a strong candidate \u2014 needs HBM_READ/WRITE_BYTES",
        "CU contention and wave quantization remain as other major factors"
      ]
    },
